  <!-- Slide 9.5: RTK — the other plugin we run -->
  <Slide id="rtk" variant="accent">
    <div class="content-slide rtk">
      <p class="overline">The Other Plugin We Run</p>
      <h2>RTK &mdash; Killing the <span class="highlight">Token Tax</span></h2>
      <p class="lead rtk__lead">
        OmO shapes <em>what</em> the agent does. <strong>RTK</strong> (Rust Token Killer) shapes how
        much it <em>costs</em> &mdash; a CLI proxy that compacts noisy command output
        <em>before</em> it ever reaches the context window. <strong>60&ndash;90% fewer tokens</strong>, same answers.
      </p>

      <div class="rtk__body">
        <!-- Left: the four mechanisms -->
        <div class="rtk__mechanisms" aria-label="How RTK compacts command output">
          <span class="rtk__col-kicker">How it strips the noise</span>
          <div class="rtk-mech rtk-mech--filter">
            <span class="rtk-mech__tag">Filter</span>
            <p>Drops comments, whitespace, and boilerplate the model never needed.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rtk-mech rtk-mech--group">
            <span class="rtk-mech__tag">Group</span>
            <p>Aggregates similar items &mdash; files by directory, errors by type.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rtk-mech rtk-mech--dedup">
            <span class="rtk-mech__tag">Dedup</span>
            <p>Collapses repeated log lines into a single line with a count.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rtk-mech rtk-mech--truncate">
            <span class="rtk-mech__tag">Truncate</span>
            <p>Keeps the relevant context, cuts the redundant tail.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Right: the token ledger -->
        <div class="rtk__ledger" aria-label="Token savings per command, one 30-minute session">
          <span class="rtk__col-kicker">One 30-min session, measured</span>
          <div class="rtk-ledger__rows">
            <div class="rtk-ledger__row">
              <code class="rtk-ledger__cmd">ls &middot; tree</code>
              <span class="rtk-ledger__nums">2,000 &rarr; 400</span>
              <span class="rtk-ledger__pct">&minus;80%</span>
            </div>
            <div class="rtk-ledger__row">
              <code class="rtk-ledger__cmd">cat &middot; read</code>
              <span class="rtk-ledger__nums">40,000 &rarr; 12,000</span>
              <span class="rtk-ledger__pct">&minus;70%</span>
            </div>
            <div class="rtk-ledger__row">
              <code class="rtk-ledger__cmd">git status</code>
              <span class="rtk-ledger__nums">3,000 &rarr; 600</span>
              <span class="rtk-ledger__pct">&minus;80%</span>
            </div>
            <div class="rtk-ledger__row">
              <code class="rtk-ledger__cmd">cargo test</code>
              <span class="rtk-ledger__nums">25,000 &rarr; 2,500</span>
              <span class="rtk-ledger__pct">&minus;90%</span>
            </div>
            <div class="rtk-ledger__row">
              <code class="rtk-ledger__cmd">pytest</code>
              <span class="rtk-ledger__nums">8,000 &rarr; 800</span>
              <span class="rtk-ledger__pct">&minus;90%</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="rtk-ledger__total">
            <span class="rtk-ledger__total-label">Whole session</span>
            <span class="rtk-ledger__total-nums">~118,000 &rarr; ~23,900</span>
            <span class="rtk-ledger__total-pct">&minus;80%</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="rtk__footer">
        <div class="rtk__strength">
          <span class="rtk__strength-kicker">Where it shines</span>
          <p>Big, repetitive, machine-generated output &mdash; test runs, build logs, <code>git</code> dumps, directory trees. The cost you pay <em>per tool call</em>, on every loop.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rtk__install">
          <span class="rtk__install-kicker">In OpenCode</span>
          <pre class="rtk__install-code"><code>"plugin": ["openrtk"]</code></pre>
          <p class="rtk__install-note">Hooks <code>tool.execute.before</code> &mdash; transparently rewrites <code>git status</code> &rarr; <code>rtk git status</code>. Single Rust binary, <code>&lt;10ms</code> overhead.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="slide-cite">
        <span class="slide-cite__tag">Source</span>
        Savings table &amp; mechanism from <a href="https://github.com/rtk-ai/rtk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">rtk-ai/rtk</a> &mdash; self-reported for a medium TS/Rust project; OpenCode plugin <a href="https://github.com/martinstannard/openrtk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">martinstannard/openrtk</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Slide>

  <!-- Slide 9.6: RTK in action — a worked pytest before/after -->
  <Slide id="rtk-example" variant="dark">
    <div class="content-slide rtk-ex">
      <p class="overline">RTK, Concretely</p>
      <h2>One <code class="rtk-ex__cmd">pytest</code> Run, <span class="highlight">Two Views</span></h2>
      <p class="lead rtk-ex__lead">
        A suite finishes: 4 pass, 1 fails. The raw output the shell hands back is mostly noise
        the model already knows it can ignore. RTK keeps the verdict and the one failure that matters.
      </p>

      <div class="rtk-ex__diff">
        <!-- BEFORE: raw pytest -->
        <div class="rtk-pane rtk-pane--before">
          <div class="rtk-pane__bar">
            <span class="rtk-pane__dots" aria-hidden="true"><i></i><i></i><i></i></span>
            <span class="rtk-pane__title">raw <code>pytest</code> &rarr; model</span>
            <span class="rtk-pane__cost rtk-pane__cost--high">~8,000 tokens</span>
          </div>
          <pre class="rtk-pane__body"><code><span class="rtk-dim">============== test session starts ==============</span>
<span class="rtk-dim">platform linux -- Python 3.11.6, pytest-8.2.0</span>
<span class="rtk-dim">rootdir: /app   collected 5 items</span>

tests/test_foo.py ..<span class="rtk-fail">F</span>..                       <span class="rtk-dim">[100%]</span>

<span class="rtk-dim">=================== FAILURES ====================</span>
<span class="rtk-dim">________________ test_something ________________</span>

<span class="rtk-dim">    def test_something():</span>
<span class="rtk-dim">></span>       <span class="rtk-dim">assert False</span>
<span class="rtk-fail">E       assert False</span>

<span class="rtk-dim">tests/test_foo.py:10: AssertionError</span>
<span class="rtk-dim">------------ Captured stdout call ---------------</span>
<span class="rtk-dim">DEBUG  loading fixtures from conftest.py</span>
<span class="rtk-dim">DEBUG  teardown complete, 3 handles closed</span>
<span class="rtk-dim">============ short test summary info ============</span>
<span class="rtk-fail">FAILED tests/test_foo.py::test_something - assert False</span>
<span class="rtk-dim">========= 4 passed, 1 failed in 0.50s ==========</span></code></pre>
        </div>

        <!-- arrow -->
        <div class="rtk-ex__arrow" aria-hidden="true">
          <span class="rtk-ex__arrow-glyph">&rarr;</span>
          <span class="rtk-ex__arrow-label">filter &middot; keep failures</span>
        </div>

        <!-- AFTER: RTK output -->
        <div class="rtk-pane rtk-pane--after">
          <div class="rtk-pane__bar">
            <span class="rtk-pane__dots" aria-hidden="true"><i></i><i></i><i></i></span>
            <span class="rtk-pane__title"><code>rtk pytest</code> &rarr; model</span>
            <span class="rtk-pane__cost rtk-pane__cost--low">~800 tokens</span>
          </div>
          <pre class="rtk-pane__body"><code><span class="rtk-ok">Pytest: 4 passed, 1 failed</span>

<span class="rtk-key">Failures:</span>
1. [<span class="rtk-fail">FAIL</span>] tests/test_foo.py::test_something
     <span class="rtk-fail">assert False</span></code></pre>
          <p class="rtk-pane__note">Verdict + the failing test + its one-line cause. Nothing the model needed is gone.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="rtk-ex__rule">
        <span class="rtk-ex__rule-tag">The rule</span>
        Read the summary for the pass/fail counts, then per failure keep the test name + up to
        <strong>3 lines</strong> that look like signal (<code>assert</code>, <code>E&hellip;</code>, a <code>.py:line</code> pointer).
        Everything else is dropped by omission &mdash; it&rsquo;s a keep-list, not a guess.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Slide>

  <!-- Slide 9.7: RTK vs. peers — three layers of the same loop -->
  <Slide id="rtk-landscape" variant="accent">
    <div class="content-slide rtk-land">
      <p class="overline">Beyond RTK</p>
      <h2>What Else Is <span class="highlight">Worth a Look</span></h2>
      <p class="lead rtk-land__lead">
        RTK is what we happen to run &mdash; but it&rsquo;s one tool in a small, fast-moving field.
        If you&rsquo;re shaping your own harness, these are the others worth knowing, and each
        attacks token waste at a <em>different point in the loop</em>.
      </p>

      <div class="rtk-land__grid">
        <!-- Layer 1: FIND -->
        <div class="land-card land-card--find">
          <div class="land-card__stage">
            <span class="land-card__stage-num">01</span>
            <span class="land-card__stage-name">Finding code</span>
          </div>
          <h3 class="land-card__tool">CodeGraph</h3>
          <p class="land-card__how">Pre-indexes the repo into a local knowledge graph (tree-sitter &rarr; SQLite). The agent <strong>queries</strong> structure instead of grepping and reading to discover it.</p>
          <div class="land-card__stats">
            <span class="land-card__stat"><strong>&minus;47%</strong> tokens</span>
            <span class="land-card__stat"><strong>&minus;58%</strong> tool calls</span>
          </div>
          <p class="land-card__meta">MCP server &middot; Node &middot; MIT &middot; 100% local</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Layer 2: RUN (RTK) -->
        <div class="land-card land-card--run">
          <div class="land-card__stage">
            <span class="land-card__stage-num">02</span>
            <span class="land-card__stage-name">Running commands</span>
          </div>
          <h3 class="land-card__tool">RTK <span class="land-card__ours-tag">we run this</span></h3>
          <p class="land-card__how">Compacts <strong>command output</strong> by command type &mdash; a per-command keep-list (knows <code>pytest</code> from <code>git</code>) applied before output reaches the model.</p>
          <div class="land-card__stats">
            <span class="land-card__stat"><strong>&minus;60&ndash;90%</strong> per command</span>
          </div>
          <p class="land-card__meta">CLI proxy / plugin &middot; Rust, <code>&lt;10ms</code> &middot; Apache&#8209;2.0</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Layer 3: COMPRESS (Headroom) -->
        <div class="land-card land-card--compress">
          <div class="land-card__stage">
            <span class="land-card__stage-num">03</span>
            <span class="land-card__stage-name">Any context</span>
          </div>
          <h3 class="land-card__tool">Headroom</h3>
          <p class="land-card__how">Routes <strong>any</strong> payload &mdash; output, logs, files, RAG, history &mdash; to type-aware compressors. Compression is <strong>reversible</strong>: the model can ask for the original.</p>
          <div class="land-card__stats">
            <span class="land-card__stat"><strong>&minus;60&ndash;95%</strong> all context</span>
          </div>
          <p class="land-card__meta">Library / proxy / MCP &middot; Python&#8239;&middot;&#8239;TS &middot; Apache&#8209;2.0</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="rtk-land__why">
        <span class="rtk-land__why-tag">Which to reach for</span>
        <p>
          Big repo, agent burns tokens just <em>finding</em> things &rarr; <strong>CodeGraph</strong>.
          Noisy command output on every loop, want zero-config &rarr; <strong>RTK</strong>.
          Want one reversible layer over <em>all</em> context, not just shell &rarr; <strong>Headroom</strong>.
          They stack &mdash; this isn&rsquo;t a pick-one.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="slide-cite">
        <span class="slide-cite__tag">Figures from each project&rsquo;s README</span>
        <a href="https://github.com/colbymchenry/codegraph" target="_blank" rel="noopener">colbymchenry/codegraph</a>
        <span class="slide-cite__sep">&middot;</span>
        <a href="https://github.com/rtk-ai/rtk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">rtk-ai/rtk</a>
        <span class="slide-cite__sep">&middot;</span>
        <a href="https://github.com/chopratejas/headroom" target="_blank" rel="noopener">chopratejas/headroom</a>
        &mdash; self-reported, vary by codebase.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Slide>

  <!-- Slide 9: Personalization thesis + ownership paths -->
  <Slide id="personalization" variant="dark">
    <div class="content-slide personalization">
      <p class="overline">The Real Lesson</p>
      <h2><span class="highlight">Own</span> Your Agent Setup</h2>
      <p class="lead personalization__lead">
        A coding-agent setup is not neutral. It is a bundle of opinions about context, tools, models, permissions, memory, and workflow.
        If you do not shape it, someone else&rsquo;s workflow shapes yours.
      </p>

      <div class="ownership">
        <div class="ownership__thesis">
          <span class="ownership__kicker">The default is already a choice</span>
          <h3>Your harness decides how the agent works.</h3>
          <p>What it reads. What it can call. Which model gets which task. When it asks. When it continues. When it stops.</p>
          <p class="ownership__line">The move is not to avoid opinions. The move is to make them yours.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="ownership__paths">
          <div class="ownership-path ownership-path--adopt">
            <span class="ownership-path__badge">Start rich</span>
            <h3>Adopt &amp; Reshape</h3>
            <p>Begin with an opinionated harness like OmO, then disable, override, and rewrite until it fits.</p>
            <span class="ownership-path__trade">Fast power. You learn by reshaping.</span>
          </div>

          <div class="ownership-path ownership-path--build">
            <span class="ownership-path__badge">Start minimal</span>
            <h3>Build Up</h3>
            <p>Begin from primitives: a small prompt, a few tools, a model API. Add only what your work actually needs.</p>
            <span class="ownership-path__trade">Maximum transparency. You assemble the power.</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="roads__destination">
        <p class="roads__destination-line">Goal: a setup that fits your work, that you understand, and that changes only when you choose.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Slide>

  <!-- Slide 11: Demo / Code example -->
  <Slide id="demo" variant="dark">
    <div class="content-slide aeval">
      <p class="overline">Example &middot; The Thesis at Its Limit</p>
      <h2>When the Agent Is <span class="highlight">the Judge</span></h2>
      <p class="lead aeval__lead">
        If a coding agent solves tasks through code, the hardest task is <em>improving another agent</em>.
        Here Claude Code is the optimizer: it reads scores, diagnoses failures, edits the subject agent&rsquo;s
        code, and re-runs &mdash; a closed loop that climbs a real metric.
      </p>

      <!-- the two agents -->
      <div class="aeval__cast">
        <div class="aeval-actor aeval-actor--subject">
          <span class="aeval-actor__role">Subject</span>
          <h3>The ML modeler</h3>
          <p>A CodeAct agent: fetch a Kaggle dataset, train a model, beat a threshold on a held-out metric.</p>
          <code class="aeval-actor__file">agent/agent.py</code>
        </div>
        <div class="aeval__cast-link" aria-hidden="true">
          <span class="aeval__cast-glyph">&#8635;</span>
          <span class="aeval__cast-label">optimizes</span>
        </div>
        <div class="aeval-actor aeval-actor--optimizer">
          <span class="aeval-actor__role">Optimizer</span>
          <h3>Claude Code <code>/loop</code></h3>
          <p>Reads the scores, finds the dominant failure, makes <strong>one</strong> minimal edit per round.</p>
          <code class="aeval-actor__file">loop/optimize.md</code>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- the 6-phase loop -->
      <div class="aeval__loop" aria-label="The six-phase optimization loop">
        <div class="aeval-phase"><span class="aeval-phase__n">1</span><span class="aeval-phase__name">Run</span><span class="aeval-phase__d">agent over all tasks</span></div>
        <span class="aeval-phase__arr" aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
        <div class="aeval-phase"><span class="aeval-phase__n">2</span><span class="aeval-phase__name">Score</span><span class="aeval-phase__d">objective + judge</span></div>
        <span class="aeval-phase__arr" aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
        <div class="aeval-phase"><span class="aeval-phase__n">3</span><span class="aeval-phase__name">Check</span><span class="aeval-phase__d">target? plateau? cap?</span></div>
        <span class="aeval-phase__arr" aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
        <div class="aeval-phase"><span class="aeval-phase__n">4</span><span class="aeval-phase__name">Diagnose</span><span class="aeval-phase__d">dominant failure</span></div>
        <span class="aeval-phase__arr" aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
        <div class="aeval-phase"><span class="aeval-phase__n">5</span><span class="aeval-phase__name">Improve</span><span class="aeval-phase__d">one edit to <code>agent.py</code></span></div>
        <span class="aeval-phase__arr" aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
        <div class="aeval-phase aeval-phase--gate"><span class="aeval-phase__n">6</span><span class="aeval-phase__name">Gate</span><span class="aeval-phase__d">commit if better, else revert</span></div>
        <span class="aeval-phase__loopback" aria-hidden="true">&#8629; loop</span>
      </div>

      <!-- what makes the eval trustworthy + link -->
      <div class="aeval__footer">
        <div class="aeval__trust">
          <span class="aeval__trust-tag">Why the score is trustworthy</span>
          <p>
            The agent never sees the test labels &mdash; a gatekeeper tool (<code>fetch_split.py</code>) strips them.
            Cheating is structurally impossible <em>before</em> you try to detect it. A judge grades method
            integrity against a rubric the loop can&rsquo;t edit.
          </p>
        </div>
